      <description>&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;There are one or two dungeons like that that I have found - you just need to do some more exploring :) That said I know what you mean - massive dungeons are really good fun. Best Dungeons of all? Dungeon Master on the Amiga and ST - they were massive, had lots of traps and buttons and you just didn't know what was around the corner :)&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;Must admit I have been scared out of my skin the number of times mobs have jumped out of the shadows at me in Oblivion - usually the first you know about it is a loud metallic crash as their swords clash against your armour!&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;Was minding my own business in Chorral today when an NPC wandered up to me and gave me another quest which was linked into the two twins I mentioned above. Not going to spoil it but on completion you have a choice of what to do with the item you retrieve. Theoretically you could also ignore the quests and just keep it for yourself :) I took one choice, which led me to yet another quest and a really nice reward (this plotline was unrelated to the above twins quest) - again there were choices to be made at the end - turn in the Thief or not - sounds simple enough, but not when you know the reasons behind it.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;Thats what I find interesting about the Morrowind/Oblivion quests. Sure most of them are go to dungeon A and kill mob B to return item C to NPC D, but there are a lot more that have a  morality to them or reveal plotlines which aren't evident if you take the 'wrong' choice. Whilst EQ and Oblivion are different games, the morality and consequence quests / plot lines are what I miss in EQ.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;Murril Merryweather&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;Spirit of Light&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;The Rathe&lt;/div&gt;</description>
