    <item>
      <title>Re: I wonder which one....</title>
      <link>http://eqforums.station.sony.com/eq/board/message?board.id=OT&amp;message.id=153772#M153772</link>
      <description>&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;p&gt;The main quest is somewhat simplistic compared to Morrowind granted - however having completed it I am now working my way around the game world. There are many little quests that you don't even get unless you overhear snippets of conversation between characters. One of which involved me rescuing a little Argonian girl from a cult. It resulted in me finding out something rather disturbing about a small hamlet. Searching that hamlet I discovered a book written in the language of the Daedra - which I am sure is translatable. The villagers talked of the 'deep ones' having returned so there may well be a Daedric shrine nearby, its something Im going to go back to once I figure out what the book says! Thats not a bad quest at all and comparable with many in Morrowind.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Then there was the one I did which resulted in two twins who didn't know each other existed being reunited. I also managed to rediscover their lost ancestral home for them and guide them back. Again a fairly involved quest.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;I have been playing now for over 100 hours. In that time I have uncovered many locations. I am convinced that some do not show up unless you activate certain quests, so there is a lot out there that you will not find unless you do so. I briefly looked at a map in the last few days with every location marked on it. On comparison to the map that I have revealed in game, I suspect I have not even found a tenth of the places out there - the revealled map was covered in landmarks.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Morrowind was something new and competely different to all that went before it. I stil play it and the two addons to this day. Morrowind had an amazing amount of in game books which gave the background of the Empire. Oblivion isn't set hundreds of years in the future or on a moon surrounding the planet, its set shortly after the events adventures of the Nevarine around Morrowind, since many are talking about the repercussions of the overthrow of the Morrowind 'gods'. That said if you do many of the Oblivion quests you are given many books by characters that don't appear on the bookshelves - and they do contain new lore.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Morrowind had a unique look amongst RPG's which really did convey a blighted land. You can clearly see however where Oblivion has its roots, the character improvement, the inventory, potion making, enchanting items, creating spells etc. It has improved dramatically with regards to the combat system, in world interaction, lockpicking etc.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;One thing I am sure of is the fact that this game is far more modular than Morrowind, it would be nice to fill in the surrounding lands as well with any add ons :)&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Both games are excellent examples of their genre, each is subtly different, both in look and gameplay, both of them are what I would call classics.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Murril Merryweather&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Spirit of Light&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;The Rathe&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt;</description>
